Exercise 15.12: Is it ever useful to declare a member function as both
override and final? Why or why not?

Answer:
It is useful since override means overriding the same virtual function in base class and final will prevent
overriding this virtual function be classes that are lower in the hierarchy.

Exercise 15.13: Given the following classes, explain each print function:
class base {
public:
    string name() { return basename; }
    virtual void print(ostream &os) { os << basename; }
private:
    string basename;
};
class derived : public base {
public:
    void print(ostream &os) { print(os); os << " " << i; }
private:
    int i;
};
If there is a problem in this code, how would you fix it?

Answer:
The base class print will print the basename, however the print in the derived class is
missing the scope operator so when calling print(os), the derived version will be called
which will cause an infinite loop;
Fix:
void print(ostream &os) { base::print(os); os << " " << i; }

